x4freetext: 1.93-m (76-in.) isochronous cyclotron.
A high-purity Ge-detector system (resolution
2.5 keV FWHM, 662 keV).
A stack of 35 NaI sealed targets were used.
Comparison with experimental I-123 yields.
Optimization of I-123 yields and purities.
thin-target yield
Target thickness
The total uncertainty in energy
calculation range from 1% at 67 MeV to 29% at 7.5 MeV.
This uncertainty includes:
* The error in the incident beam energy  - 1%
* The error in the range values  - 1%
* The error in the NaI-target density  - 1%
* The error in the NaI-target thickness (weighing
errors)   - 1%
The excitation functions reported here have energy
uncertainties ranging from +-0.55 MeV at 66.9 MeV,
to +-2.2 MeV at 7.5 MeV.
The total uncertainty in the cross section
and radionuclide-yield values was calculated as 9%.
The total uncertainty includes:
The uncertainty in the beam-current integration
The uncertainty in the calibration sources
The uncertainty in the detector efficiency
The uncertainty in the counting geometry.
The uncertainty in the decay corrections.
The uncertainty in the gamma-ray abundances
The uncertainty in the integration
routines(average) is 3% (the maximum uncertainty in
the integration routines is 8%).
/By authors/ Average proton energies at the geometrical
center of each NaI target are given.
